The path to nuclear disarmament
NEW YORK – Mass destruction weapons and disarmament represent one of the most challenging tasks that the world is currently facing. One of my priorities as Secretary-General of the United Nations is to promote the global common good and find solutions to problems that respect no boundaries.
A world without nuclear weapons is a universal good of the utmost importance.
My interest in this topic is partly based on personal experiences.
My home country, South Korea, suffered under the devastation of conventional war and was exposed to the threat of nuclear weapons and other mass destruction weapons.
However, such threat scenarios exist, of course, not only in Asia.
Although the use of atomic weapons has long been considered taboo, disarmament remains merely an endeavor.
Is a taboo that applies only to the use of such weapons sufficient in any case?
When it comes to nuclear weapons, individual states make the most important decisions.
However, the UN plays a crucial role in this process.
We offer a central forum where states can agree on norms that serve their common interests.
We analyze and educate to achieve our agreed-upon goals, and we advocate for them.
Most states have decided to forgo nuclear weapons and have consolidated their commitments under the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty.
However, some states view such weapons as status symbols, and others see them as the ultimate deterrent against an attack with nuclear weapons, which explains the approximately 26,000 still existing weapons primarily.
Unfortunately, the doctrine of nuclear deterrence is contagious, making non-proliferation more difficult and giving rise to new risks that nuclear weapons will be used.
The world remains concerned about nuclear activities in North Korea and Iran, and there is broad support for efforts to address these concerns through peaceful means.
There are also concerns that we are on the verge of a "nuclear renaissance," as nuclear energy is seen as a clean energy alternative in times of increasing efforts to combat climate change.
The main concern is that this will lead to the production and use of more fissile material, which must be protected from proliferation and terrorist threats.
The obstacles to disarmament are massive.
However, the costs and risks of their alternatives are never given the attention they deserve.
Let's think about the enormous opportunity costs of high military budgets.
According to the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute, military expenditures rose to over $1.3 trillion last year.
Ten years ago, the Brookings Institution published a study estimating the total costs of nuclear weapons in the United States alone to be over $5.8 trillion, including future cleanup costs.
That's a massive investment by any definition, which could have been used for many other productive purposes.
Concerns about the costs of nuclear weapons and the dangers they pose have sparked a global idea of how nuclear disarmament could be given new life.
We have experienced the UN Arms Control Commission under Hans Blix, the New Agenda Coalition, and Norway's Seven Nation Initiative.
Australia and Japan have founded the International Commission for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament.
Civil groups and nuclear-armed states have also submitted proposals, such as the Hoover Plan, which was introduced by Henry Kissinger.
I would like to propose my own Five-Point Plan.
First: I call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty, especially the nuclear powers, to comply with their obligations under the treaty and to initiate negotiations on effective measures that lead to nuclear disarmament.
They could agree on a framework agreement for separate, mutually verifiable instruments.
Or they could negotiate a nuclear weapons convention supported by a strong control system, as has been proposed in the UN for a long time.
I have sent a draft of such a convention, which provides a good starting point, to all UN member states.
The nuclear powers should actively engage with this issue at the UN Conference on Disarmament in Geneva, the only multilateral negotiating forum for disarmament in the world, together with other states.
The world would also welcome a resumption of bilateral negotiations between the US and Russia, with the goal of reducing their arsenals strongly and verifiably.
The governments should also invest more in control research and development.
The UK's proposal to hold a conference of nuclear powers on control is a concrete step in the right direction.
Secondly: The permanent members of the Security Council should start discussing security issues in the process of nuclear disarmament.
They could clearly reassure non-nuclear states that they will not be victims of a nuclear attack or its threat.
The Council could also convene a summit on nuclear disarmament.
States that are not members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty should stop their nuclear weapons programs and enter into their own disarmament commitments.
Thirdly: Unilateral moratoriums on nuclear tests and the production of fissile materials should only be allowed to a certain extent.
We need new efforts to bring the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty into force, as well as incentives for the Disarmament Conference to immediately and without conditions take up discussions on a treaty on fissile materials.
I support the establishment of nuclear-free zones in Central Asia and Africa and strongly advocate for efforts to establish such zones in the Middle East.
In addition, I urgently call on all members of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to conclude their safety agreements with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and voluntarily introduce the stricter safety provisions of the Additional Protocol.
Fourthly: The nuclear powers often circulate descriptions of what they are doing to achieve these goals.
However, these reports rarely reach the public.
I would like to ask the nuclear powers to send such materials to the UN Secretariat and contribute to their further dissemination.
The fact that there is no reliable estimate of the total number of nuclear weapons underscores the need for greater transparency.
And finally, various additional measures are required.
This includes the elimination of other types of mass destruction weapons, new efforts against terrorism using mass destruction weapons, a limitation on the production and trade of conventional weapons, and new arms bans, including for rockets and space weapons.
If there are real, verified progress in disarmament, the ability to eliminate the nuclear threat will grow exponentially.
By gradually eliminating the deadliest weapons in the world and their components, we make it more difficult to carry out terrorist attacks using mass destruction weapons.
These proposals offer a new start, not only for disarmament, but also for strengthening our system of international peace and international security.
